proper noun.description: A historic city in northwestern Virginia, in the Shenandoah Valley; population 25,897 (est. 2008).

A city in southern England, the county town of Hampshire; population 43,800 (est. 2009). Known to the Romans as Venta Belgarum, it became capital of the West Saxon kingdom of Wessex in 519. It is the site of Winchester College, one of the oldest private schools in England, founded by the bishop of Winchester, William of Wykeham, in 1382.

noun.description: A disk drive in a sealed unit containing a high-capacity hard disk and the read-write heads.

origin: From the name of name of Oliver F. Winchester (1810–80), the American manufacturer of the rifle. Winchester (sense 2) is so named because its original numerical designation corresponded to the caliber of the rifle.
